The ultimate off-road adventures are destined to take place on Mars &amp;#8212; two-wheel-drive vehicles need not apply.<br>
<br>
Talcum-fine dust, sand, house-sized rocks and one-third as much gravity as Earth are among the things that manned Martian rovers might have to tackle, say engineers and their students, who are working on prototypes of what astronauts will drive around the Red Planet.<br>
<br>
  <br>
 <br>
&quot;We have to decide what we really want to drive the rovers over,&quot; said Jeremy Burns, student leader of the University of Michigan's 4WD Martian rover team. He and other groups working on prototype Mars rovers presented reports earlier this week at the annual meeting of the Mars Society at Stanford University in California.<br>
Taking lessons from rock crawling competitions and dune buggy racers, Burns said no rover will be able to do it all. <br>
<br>
&quot;The way you really get through sand is to put as much sand out the back end,&quot; said Burns. That can be done with big baffle-treaded tires, low clearance and lots of high-gear power.<br>
<br>
To get over large rocks, the rover needs high clearance, a flexible frame, a very high torque drive train, and ultra-low gearing to crawl like a bug over obstacles.<br>
<br>
One way to incorporate both rock and sand traversing abilities is to use airbags &amp;#8212; the kind that raise and lower the rover &amp;#8212; not the kind that protect occupants. Another good idea would be an independent suspension, allowing each wheel to get power separately &amp;#8212; enabling the rover to spin around like a tank. This would also get rid of the axle between wheels and give the vehicle more clearance, said Burns.<br>
<br>
But what if you need to live in the rover for two weeks while out rockhounding in the Martian countryside? Rovers will need their own air supply, living quarters and energy enough to keep moving more than a hundred million miles from the nearest filling station.<br>
<br>
Nuclear power or fuel cells are the logical power plants, said Chad Ohlandt, a Ph.D. engineering student at Michigan State University. Solar power won't work, he said, because rovers are too small to put enough solar panels on and the sunshine on Mars is pretty weak. Solar cells are also too fragile for the harsh Martian environment.<br>
<br>
Then there's the matter of comfort. <br>
<br>
&quot;I for one am not very keen on traveling in the rover we're building because it's not very comfortable,&quot; said Ben Cairns, head of another rover project with the Mars Society Australia. <br>
